3:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["How Funding Works on ","Orderly Network"]}]
4:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices across its shared liquidity layer. The funding mechanism operates independently on each frontend partner while sharing the same underlying order book, creating potential rate discrepancies. Long positions pay funding when rates are positive, while shorts receive payments, with settlements occurring automatically through smart contracts. The decentralized nature means funding rates can deviate from centralized exchanges due to different user bases and liquidity patterns across partner DEXs."}]
5:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","TRX","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TRX perpetuals offer compelling arbitrage opportunities due to TRON's staking rewards creating natural long bias among holders, often leading to consistently positive funding rates. The token's large trading volume and established DeFi ecosystem generate significant perpetual interest, while TRX's correlation with broader crypto markets creates predictable funding rate patterns. Orderly's multi-chain infrastructure allows arbitrageurs to capture rate differences between NEAR and Ethereum-based TRX positions simultaneously."}]]}]
6:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TRX funding rates on Orderly Network typically range from -0.05% to 0.15% per funding period, with positive rates dominating during bull markets due to staking yield expectations. The 1-hour interval creates more granular opportunities compared to 8-hour systems, allowing traders to capture shorter-term sentiment shifts. Funding rates often spike during TRX ecosystem announcements or major TRON network upgrades, sometimes reaching 0.3% per hour during extreme events. The shared liquidity model means rates can differ significantly from isolated DEX implementations, especially during low liquidity periods when frontend-specific demand creates imbalances."}]]}]
7:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-DEX arbitrage opportunities emerge when different Orderly frontend partners experience varying user demand for TRX longs or shorts. The shared order book creates unique situations where funding rates can be arbitraged against spot holdings across NEAR and EVM chains simultaneously. Traders can exploit rate differentials between Orderly and centralized exchanges by maintaining opposite positions, particularly effective during TRX staking reward distributions when CEX rates spike. The 0.02%/0.05% maker/taker fee structure makes high-frequency funding arbitrage viable for positions above $10,000, with optimal strategies focusing on rate spreads exceeding 0.1% per period."}]]}]
8:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly's dependency on frontend partners creates counterparty risk beyond typical DEX smart contract exposure, as interface outages can prevent position management during critical periods. Cross-chain arbitrage introduces bridge risks when moving TRX between NEAR and Ethereum ecosystems, particularly during network congestion or bridge maintenance. The shared liquidity model means sudden large trades on any partner frontend can impact funding calculations across the entire network, creating unexpected rate movements. Slippage risk increases during low liquidity periods when the shared order book becomes thin, potentially eroding arbitrage profits despite favorable funding rate spreads."}]]}]
9:["$","$Le",null,{"items":[{"question":"How do TRX funding rates differ across Orderly Network frontend partners?","answer":"While all frontends share the same underlying order book, funding rates can vary slightly due to different user bases and trading patterns on each interface. Partners like WOOFi or Ref Finance may see different long/short ratios, creating temporary rate discrepancies that arbitrageurs can exploit."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage TRX funding rates between NEAR and Ethereum sides of Orderly?","answer":"Yes, Orderly's cross-chain architecture allows arbitrage between NEAR and EVM positions, though you'll need to account for bridge costs and timing. This strategy works best during significant rate divergences when bridge fees are justified by the funding rate differential."},{"question":"What's the minimum position size for profitable TRX funding arbitrage on Orderly?","answer":"Given the 0.02%/0.05% fee structure and typical TRX funding rates of 0.05-0.15% per hour, positions above $5,000 generally provide meaningful returns. However, optimal profitability typically requires $15,000+ positions to overcome transaction costs and potential slippage."},{"question":"How does Orderly's 1-hour funding interval impact TRX arbitrage strategies?","answer":"The shorter intervals create more frequent opportunities but require active monitoring and faster execution. TRX rates can shift quickly during TRON ecosystem events, making the hourly settlements advantageous for capturing short-term sentiment changes that 8-hour systems would miss."}]}]
